\fs22
\cf1
{statement of work (SOW) different from a contract statement of work? What are so
me of the requirements for creating a contract SOW?}\plain \f0
\fs2
\cf1
{\par
}\plain \f0
\fs2
\cf1
\pard
\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0
\li0\ri0\fi0
\ql\sa1\plain \f0
\fs22
\cf1
{\par
}\plain \f0
\fs22
\cf1
\pard
\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0
\li0\ri0\fi0
\ql\tx0\tx634\tx1958\tx2592\tx3916\tx4550\tx5874\tx6508
{ANS:\tab }\plain \f0
\fs22
\cf1
{\par
}\plain \f0
\fs22
\cf1
\pard
\widctlpar\keep\hyphpar0
\li0\ri0\fi0
\ql\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{The statement of work (SOW) is a description of the work required for the procur
ement. If a SOW is used as part of a contract to describe only the work required 
for that particular contract, it is called a contract statement of work. The cont
ract SOW is a type of scope statement that describes the work in sufficient detai
l to allow prospective suppliers to determine if they are capable of providing th
e goods and services required and to determine an appropriate price. \par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{\par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{A contract SOW should be clear, concise, and as complete as possible. It should 
describe all services required and include performance reporting. It is important
 to use appropriate words in a contract SOW such as must instead of may. It shoul
d specify the products and services required for the project, use industry terms,
 and refer to industry standards.\par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{\par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{It should specify the location of the work, the expected period of performance, 
specific deliverables and when they are due, applicable standards, acceptance cri
teria, and special requirements. A good contract SOW gives bidders a better under
standing of the buyer\'92
s expectations. A contract SOW should become part of the of
ficial contract to ensure that the buyer gets what the supplier bid on.}\plain \f0
